Introduction

In homework3, I use the dataset mobile-price-classification to compare multinomial logistic regression and KNN model.This data is downloaded from Kaggle-Mobile Price Classification.

My homework is organized as follows. Part 1 briefly introduces this data and gets some basic analysis. Part 2 presents the results of multinomial logistic regression and KNN. In part 3, I will try to visualize decision boundaries.

Part 1

This data provides many features of a mobile phone(eg: RAM,Internal Memory, Battery power, pixel,speed etc) and its selling price. What I want to do is to find out the relation between the features and mobile price. First I will show you some plots between these variables.

mobile<-read.csv("E:/博二/微观计量/mobile-price-classification/train.csv")
names(mobile)
##  [1] "battery_power" "blue"          "clock_speed"   "dual_sim"     
##  [5] "fc"            "four_g"        "int_memory"    "m_dep"

## [13] "px_width"      "ram"           "sc_h"          "sc_w"         
## [17] "talk_time"     "three_g"       "touch_screen"  "wifi"         
## [21] "price_range"
dim(mobile)
## [1] 2000   21
#transfer numeric to factor
mobile$price_range<-as.factor(mobile$price_range)

attach(mobile)
par(mfrow=c(2,2))
boxplot(int_memory~price_range,xlab="price_range",ylab="int_memory")
boxplot(n_cores~price_range,xlab="price_range",ylab="n_cores")
boxplot(mobile_wt~price_range,xlab="price_range",ylab="mobile_wt")
boxplot(px_height~price_range,xlab="price_range",ylab="px_height")

par(mfrow=c(1,1))
require(ggplot2)
ggplot(mobile,aes(x=ram,y=battery_power,color=price_range))+
  scale_color_manual(values = c("pink","yellow","blue","darkblue"))+geom_point(size=1.5)

From above plots,we can see that only ram(Random Access Memory) has a positive correlationship with mobile price.

#(2) KNN
require(class)
vars<-names(mobile) %in% c("price_range")
mobile_tr_x<-mobile_tr[!vars]
mobile_te_x<-mobile_te[!vars]
s.tr_x<-scale(mobile_tr_x)
s_te_x<-scale(mobile_te_x)
knn.pred <- knn(s.tr_x,s_te_x,mobile_tr$price_range,k=8,prob=TRUE)
t<-table(knn.pred,mobile_te$price_range,dnn=c("predicted","true"))
t

1-sum(diag(t))/sum(t)
## [1] 0.495

In above codes, I choose K=8, then I use CV to choose the best K and predict.

require(caret)
knnfit<-train(price_range~.,data=mobile_tr,method="knn",
              trControl=trainControl(method="repeatedcv",repeats = 3),
              preProcess=c("center","scale"),tuneLength=50)
plot(knnfit)

knnpred<-predict(knnfit,mobile_te)
t<-table(knnpred,mobile_te$price_range,dnn=c("predicted","true"))
t
##          true
## predicted   0   1   2   3
##         0 112  29   0   0
##         1  38  85  51   3
##         2   0  26  82  55
##         3   0   0  11 108
# misclassification rate
1-sum(diag(t))/sum(t)
## [1] 0.355

Comparing the misclassification rate, we can find the Multinomial Logistic Regression model is better.The result of multinomial logistic regression shows that battery power, ram, camera pixel,and inter memory have significant positive relations with mobile price. And mobile depth, weight and charge time are inverse. The results are consistent with our common sense.

Part 3

In this part, I choose battery_power, ram and price_range to take the multinomial logistic regression and visualize the decision boundaries.

logitfit2<-multinom(price_range~ram+battery_power,data=mobile)
## # weights:  16 (9 variable)
## initial  value 2772.588722 
## iter  10 value 1795.439579
## iter  20 value 788.039013
## iter  30 value 787.952111
## final  value 786.941208 
## converged
x<-expand.grid(ram=pretty(ram,50),battery_power=pretty(battery_power,50))
logitfit_pr<-predict(logitfit2,x,type ="probs")
require(lattice)
fig2.main <- xyplot(battery_power ~ ram, groups=price_range,
                    auto.key=list(space="right"),
                    aspect=1, par.settings = simpleTheme(pch=20),grid=TRUE,alpha=.5)
diff1 <- apply(logitfit_pr, 1, function(x)x[1]-max(x[-1]))
diff2 <- apply(logitfit_pr, 1, function(x)x[2]-max(x[-2]))
diff3 <- apply(logitfit_pr, 1, function(x)x[3]-max(x[-3]))
diff4 <- apply(logitfit_pr, 1, function(x)x[4]-max(x[-4]))

fig2.addlayer1 <- latticeExtra::as.layer(
  contourplot(diff1 ~ ram*battery_power,data=x,at=0,labels="",lty=3,lwd=1.5), axes=FALSE)
fig2.addlayer2 <- latticeExtra::as.layer(
  contourplot(diff2 ~ ram*battery_power,data=x,at=0,labels="",lty=2,lwd=1.5), axes=FALSE)
fig2.addlayer3 <- latticeExtra::as.layer(
  contourplot(diff3 ~ ram*battery_power,data=x,at=0,labels="",lty=2,lwd=1.5), axes=FALSE)
fig2.addlayer4 <- latticeExtra::as.layer(
  contourplot(diff4 ~ ram*battery_power,data=x,at=0,labels="",lty=2,lwd=1.5), axes=FALSE)
fig2.main + fig2.addlayer1 + fig2.addlayer2 + fig2.addlayer3+fig2.addlayer4
trellis.focus("toplevel")
panel.text(0.35,0.5,"0",font=2)
panel.text(0.45,0.5,"1",font=2)
panel.text(0.55,0.5,"2",font=2)
panel.text(0.65,0.5,"3",font=2)
trellis.unfocus()

detach(mobile)
